UML:TaggedValue.value: A TextualExpressions allows a fallback to a programming language if this is necessary. It can contain any arbitrary expression, for which language and language version, are used to interpret the expression at runtime or compile time. TextualExpressions also allow the use of script languages or small DSLs in the context of SDMs.
Expressions are used in patterns to specify non-structural constraints (e.g. constraints on attribute values). Expressions are also used to construct method calls, specify return values etc.

UML:TaggedValue.value: A BinaryExpression has a right-hand side and a left-hand side, which can be arbitrary expressions.

A LiteralExpression is to be interpreted "literally" meaning exactly how it is. Examples are "size", 4, true. A LiteralExpression is not to be confused with a variable like size, which -- in general -- has nothing to do with the literal String "size". LiteralExpressions are TypedElements, and their "type" is used to interpret the literal value correctly (i.e. for type == EString, "5" would be interpreted as "5", for EInt, as Integer.parseInt("5")).
A ComparisonExpression has, in addition to LHS and RHS, an Operator that defines how the expressions are to be compared.
A ComparingOperator represents the typical mathematical operators used in inequalities: <, <=, >, >=, ==, !=
